$MOOMOO Investment Thesis

The Original Bull Meme, Now On-Chain

1. Origin: The First Bull Market Meme on 4chan
• $MOOMOO is based on Moomoo the Bull, first posted July 12, 2018 on 4chan’s /biz/ board.
• Thread titled: “Bulls officially have a mascot” — predates all references to “Mumu.”
• Dozens of anons refined the meme, naming the character “Moo Moo” before “Mumu” even emerged.

Bottom line: $MOOMOO is not a derivative — it’s the source of the entire bull meme archetype.

⸻

2. Narrative Fit: Bull Cycles Need Bull Symbols
• Bobo the Bear dominates bear market memes — Moomoo is his narrative counterpart.
• As retail sentiment flips bullish, traders naturally search for a mascot to channel euphoria.
• $MOOMOO offers instant recognition, rooted in crypto-native culture.

This isn’t forced branding — it’s latent demand aligned with market psychology.

⸻

3. Competitive Advantage: Zero-Meme Redundancy
• Dog coins? Saturated. Frogs? Peaked.
• $MOOMOO is the only tokenized bull meme with 2018 provenance and community roots.
• No other meme project owns the “bull market” identity this authentically.

⸻

4. Timing: Early Narrative Entry
• Bull market underway. Retail re-engaging.
• Most meme tokens chase hype. $MOOMOO delivers a story that predates the cycle and fits perfectly.
• The Moomoo vs Bobo dynamic creates long-term meme flywheel potential.

⸻

Conclusion

$MOOMOO is a memecoin with:
 • Provenance (2018 /biz/ origin)
 • Cultural equity (OG status, pre-Mumu)
 • Narrative fit (bull market mascot)
 • Scarcity (no viable competitors)

High-meme asymmetry, deep roots, and perfect timing.
Not just a bet on a coin — a bet on the bull run itself.

5bKtwZ3EYNA9wYApXgXLEbzZLG5QwMMTYSGfQBhJ.description: Chinese talisman culture, known as fulu (符箓), is a traditional practice rooted in Taoism. It involves creating and using special paper charms inscribed with symbolic characters, patterns, or spells. These talismans are believed to possess spiritual power to ward off evil, bring good luck, ensure protection, or promote healing. Practitioners, often Taoist priests, draw talismans with specific rituals, using cinnabar ink and precise calligraphy. Used in religious ceremonies, exorcisms, or daily life, fulu reflects a deep connection to Chinese spirituality and cosmology.
